Commentary.Commentary: As for South Africa, wickets did come for them but it was a little too late following the opening masterclass by Rohit Sharma and Mayank Agarwal. The pick of the bowlers would be Keshav Maharaj and Vernon Philander. However, seeing the ball turn so much late in the evening, the South African batters would be a bit concerned. Join us in a while for the first innings of South Africa as the Indians look to take some early wickets.

All the work started from the new Indian opening pair of Mayank Agarwal and Rohit Sharma. The two formed a massive opening stand of 317 runs before Rohit Sharma departed for a superbly made 176. Mayank Agarwal continued the good work after his partner departed as he stitched two 50-plus stands with Virat Kohli and Ajinkya Rahane respectively. Mayank Agarwal stayed at the crease for the longest time as he played a mind-boggling innings of 215 runs. He departed in an attempt to increase the run rate towards the end of the day but not before making a mark on the match. Jadeja and Saha provided the finishing touches as the Indian total crossed the 500-run mark.

Brilliant performance from India as they have declared on 502/7. The home team put up a daunting total in front of an inexperienced South African team and it will be interesting to see how they respond on this turning surface.

King Kohli walks out to bat when the match is going through a transitional phase. How much can the skipper and Agarwal build up on the platform already set?

OUT! TIMBER! WHAT A START! What a start to the second session by Vernon Philander and the off stump has gone for a spin! Philander pitches this one on the middle and off pole line. It nips away after pitching, beating the outside edge of Pujara's bat and hits the top of off pole as the stump goes cartwheeling. Philander has struck right after the Lunch break and Pujara walks back to the pavilion after scoring just 6 runs. This is the 23rd time that Pujara has been bowled in Test matches. A way back for the Proteas?

We are back for the second session of the day! Mayank Agarwal and Cheteshwar Pujara make their way out to the middle along with the South African players. Cheteshwar Pujara will be on strike for the next over facing Vernon Philander.
... Day 2, Session 2 ...

India on top! That is all one can say after the first session's play on Day 2. The hosts started the day with 202 runs on the board with all 10 wickets in hand. Rohit Sharma and Mayank Agarwal accelerated towards the latter part of the session. There were a couple of chances here and there for the South Africans but nothing of note except for the dropped catch of Rohit Sharma. However, he departed after playing a beautiful knock of 176 runs and it is now Pujara and Agarwal at the crease. Agarwal also will be looking to build on after scoring his maiden Test ton. What will be the story of the Test match after the Lunch break on Day 2? Stay tuned to find out and join us at 1210 local (0640 GMT) for an extended second session of play.
Good length ball on middle and off, Agarwal blocks it out. And that will be LUNCH ON DAY 2!
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.

OUT! STUMPED! Finally a wicket for the Proteas and the Hitman has to return to the pavilion. A wonderful innings by him comes to an end with him being dismissed just one short of his best Test score. Maharaj floats this one just outside the off pole line, Rohit looks to prod forward and block it out but the ball spins away and Sharma misses it completely. He loses his balance and his foot is dragged out of the crease as Quinton de Kock dislodges the bails from behind. The square leg umpire raises his finger and Sharma has to walk back. The South African players go up and congratulate him on his great innings as he is dismissed on 176. The massive 317-run partnership comes to an end. It has given very little chance for South Africa to make a comeback into the game.

The Protea players make their way out to the middle with just one aim in mind - dismiss the Indian openers as fast as they can and then start building on from there. The Indian openers, Rohit Sharma and Mayank Agarwal walk out to the middle as well with the former taking strike. Vernon Philander to continue the proceedings for the visitors on Day 2.

Pitch Report - On being asked about the pitch, Mr. Sunil Gavaskar suggests that nothing much has changed about the pitch. There might be a little more turn today but not much bounce on this track. Mr. Gavaskar further suggests that because of the overnight rain yesterday, the fast bowlers might be able to use it to their advantage in the first ten overs of the day.

Good morning folks! India were absolutely dominant on Day 1, crossing the 200-run mark without losing any wickets. They certainly looked like adding more to the score before the heavens opened up and washed out the third session. Rohit Sharma silenced his critics with a wonderful unbeaten century and would be looking to add more to his tally today. His partner, Mayank Agarwal is close to reaching his first Test ton and would be hoping to accomplish the milestone early in the first session. The Proteas had a horrid time yesterday with none of their bowlers having a good day. They would be hoping for a better performance as this match is slowly getting out of hand. It is a new day and both teams will have to start fresh. There is rain predicted today as well but let us hope that it stays away and we have an exciting day of Test cricket ahead of us. Join us in a while for all the action from Visakhapatnam!
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

South Africa, on the other hand, need wickets and that too quickly if they are to make a comeback in this game. Their bowlers just did not look at their best on Day 1 and they need a better performance on Day 2. Will they fight back or will the Indians continue their dominance? Join us for Day 2. Till then, take care and goodbye!

Day 1 though was all about the Indians. Everything went right for them. They won the toss, elected to bat and their two openers are still unbeaten. One crossed his ton in his first game as an opener and the other is eyeing his first in Tests. The platform is laid for a huge first innings score and India will be exactly looking for that as they would be aiming to bat only once.

So the inevitable has happened! Play has been CALLED OFF for the day. That was always on the cards once they went off as it seemed improbable for the lights to improve and the rain worsened things further. A whole session is lost today so we probably will be covering up for it in the coming days.
Update 1455 local (0925 GMT) - No change in the update. It is pelting down and the covers are firmly placed. It is also very dark out there. Chances of any play today looks bleak.

We are back! The Indian openers are marking their guard once again as they will look to resume their innings. Vernon Philander is all set to continue his over. ALL THIS IS SOMETHING I WISH I COULD HAVE WRITTEN! Unfortunately, it is raining at the moment, actually, there is lightning out there. The whole ground is covered and we are in for a delay here.

The openers have taken India from strength to strength. The second session too belongs to India. Hitman, looks on course to be the solution to India's opening dilemma. However, just as a few half-chances chances seem to be getting created, the umpires went off the field for bad light. Let's hope, the sun comes back out and we get some action quickly. There it is! 100 for Rohit Sharma. 4th in Tests. What a way to grab the opportunity presented. He was struggling to get into the side, here, he gets a chance as an opener and he responds with a ton. Outstanding knock and the whole stadium is on its feet applauding the effort. He gets to the milestone after cutting the ball through point for one. He would now be eyeing a big one, maybe a double ton. He has three in ODIs, can he get his first in Tests here? Also, the bowler has overstepped so it is no ball too.

Ohhhh! Rohit had his heart in his mouth for a moment there. KM floats it up on off, it may have stuck in the surface a little. Rohit looks to drive but does so uppishly, it lands just short of short covers.

SIX! one after the other. This time it's over the long on boundary, Gets to the pitch of the ball and launches it. This one went further.

Floats it outside off, Sharma defends it off the front foot.

Another defensive stroke to this delivery on off.
Lands it on middle, Mayank prods forward and keeps it out.
Floats it up outside off, Agarwal strokes it to covers.

NO BALL!  It is on middle, Agarwal keeps it out. The No ball was due to the silly point fielder encroaching the pitch.

DRINKS! One hour through the second session, Rohit Sharma and Mayank Agarwal have further strengthened India's stranglehold on this match. They're on course to get their respective centuries. Stay tuned to find out!

FOUR! Wide outside off and short, Sharma rocks back and powerfully slaps the ball to the mid-wicket boundary.

Around off on a fullish length this time, Agarwal keeps it out with ease.
A fuller one around off this time, Agarwal is solid in his block as he pushes it towards cover.
Flatter one around off, Agarwal taps it towards cover.
Shortish ball outside off, Rohit goes back and punches it towards deep point for a single.
A flighted ball around off, Rohit lunges to block it towards point.

Good bumper, Agarwal ducks under it to let it pass.

On the pads, worked through backward square leg for a single.
In the corridor of uncertainty, Agarwal shoulders arms to it.

Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
Outside off played to point.
Short and on middle, Sharma pulls it to square leg for a single. Piedt does a neat job in the field to keep it down to a single.

The last ball also is defended as it is bowled on the stumps.

Well bowled but well played too! Rohit comes down the track, Maharaj shortens his length and bowls it outside off. Rohit adjusts and slaps it through covers for one.

Loopy ball on off, Rohit prods forward and keeps it out.

Blocks yet again. Sharma and Agarwal are taking calculated risks.
Shortish in length around off, it's defended off the back foot
FOUR! Back of a length outside off, Sharma camps on the back foot and steers it past the diving gully fielder for a boundary.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
Good length ball on off, Agarwal plays it to the off side for a single.
Leg bye. LBW Appeal! But it's not to be. Angled in, it hits him on the pads, but the ball is going down leg and the umpire ignores it. The Proteas too do not go for a review. They sneak in a leg bye.

The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.

SIX! That is some way to get to a half ton. What a shot. Wow! Probably the shot of the game so far. It is Agarwal's 4th fifty in this format. Maharaj floats this up outside off, Agarwal goes  inside out, lofts it with utmost ease over covers and it carries all the way. A big one is on the offer for him too.
Sharma comes down the track but it is a short ball. He pushes it down to long on for one.

FOUR! 1st 100-run stand for the opening wicket for India after 24 innings. Full on the pads, Agarwal powers it with his wrists to the mid-wicket boundary. The mid on fielder gave it a chase but it was in vain. First runs after 22 balls.
On Middle and off, Agarwal gets an inside edge onto his pads.
Full outside off, Agarwal pushes it to the covers.

Gets within the line of the ball and blocks.

Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
Short outside off now, Agarwal cuts it and Markram at backward point makes a diving stop.
Full ball on the pads, squirted to square leg. No run.
A little shorter this time, outside off, Agarwal flat bats it to point.
Fullish ball on off, Agarwal defends it off the front foot.

Another one on middle, Rohit easily keeps it out.
On middle, this is also defended.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Well fielded! Rohit comes down the track and works it to the right of the bowler. He dives and pushes it towards short mid-wicket, saves a run.
Tosses it up on off, Rohit lunges and keeps it out.
Fuller and on on middle, Agarwal blocks it out.
Persists with the short pitch line outside off, in an attempt to guide it to third man, Agarwal plays it into the pitch.
Bangs it in short outside, it doesn't rise much. Agarwal cuts it to deep point for a couple.
Full ball on middle, Sharma flicks off the front foot to mid-wicket for a single.
Comes on the front foot and defends.
Good length outside off, Sharma plays it with soft hands to the off side.
Vernon Philander to bowl from the other end.
On the pads, Agarwal looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
On the off pole, Agarwal keeps it out.
Very full this time, Rohit eases it down to long on for one.
Attacks the stumps now and it is slightly fuller. Kept out.

FOUR! Rohit continues from where he left off before the break! First runs in this session is in the form of a boundary. Slightly short and outside off, Rohit goes back and punches it through covers, it is in the gap and it races away.
Starts off with a flatter delivery on off, Rohit defends it out.

We are back for the afternoon session! The South African players make their way out to the middle. The Indian openers, Mayank Agarwal and Rohit Sharma, will resume their innings. For the visitors, Keshav Maharaj will begin proceedings. Here we go...
... Day 1, Session 2 ...

South Africa, on the other hand, did start off really well, their pacers were brilliant with the new ball. However, once the shine came off and the ball stopped seaming around, their bowlers looked ineffective. The spinners haven't got a lot out of the wicket and hence, have been negotiated with ease. They need a couple of wickets to get back into the game. Do they have a hero in them who would put his hand up and do that or will India continue to dominate after the break? Join us to find out in a bit.

India's session without a doubt! Exactly the kind of start they would have wanted after winning the toss and electing to bat. Their openers did struggle a bit against the moving ball but did not lose their wicket. Once the conditions got easy, runs came thick and fast, especially for Rohit who played the spinners really well. Sharma got to an excellent fifty in his first innings as a Test opener. Credit to Agarwal as well, he too has played sensibly and both the batsmen are on the verge of laying down a platform for a big first innings score.
Covers the line of the ball and defends. LUNCH ON DAY 1.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
Short again, angled on middle this time. Agarwal gets out of the line of the ball.
Drops it short outside off, Agarwal shoulders arms to let it through.

In the air... just wide! FOUR! Fifty up for Rohit. He brings it up in a streaky manner but he won't care. Excellent start for him as a Test opener. 11th in this format. It has been a very entertaining knock from him so far. Got through the initial tough phase and now looks extremely good out there. He has a chance to make it big here. He brings out the sweep shot but due to the extra bounce, it catches the top edge. Goes uppishly but wide of Rabada at backward square leg who puts in a dive. The ball then races to the fence.
The batsman works it down the leg side.
Well bowled! Sees Rohit come down the track so shortens his length. Rohit does well to adjust and keep it out. He played it well though as there was extra bounce there. Played it with soft hands.
Gives it a lot of air and lands it on off, Rohit drives it to covers.

A freebie! A full toss but all Agarwal could do is, hit it down to long on for one.
Full toss on leg, played to mid on.
Camps on the back foot and blocks the ball.
Angled further on the pads, Rohit flicks it to mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
Comes in with the angle again, Sharma defends it as well.
Angled in on middle, Sharma blocks it out.
Rohit uncomfortably gets a leading edge to a shortish delivery outside off to point, where the fielder dives and saves a run.
A dot to end! Flatter and on off, it is kept out.
A single now as this is pushed through covers for one. A boundary away from a 50 now.

FOUR! Lovely use of the wrists there by Rohit. He skips down the track again and gets to the pitch of it this time. Does not go hard and just whips it through mid-wicket. The ball races away to the fence. Rohit is into his own now.
Lands this on middle, Rohit prods forward and keeps it out.
Rohit comes down the track but does not get to the pitch of the ball. Ends up pushing it to mid on.
Starts off with a very full ball on middle, Rohit jams it out.

A maiden! Another length ball and on off, Agarwal keeps it out.
One more delivery angled into the batter, Agarwal stays back and keeps it out.
Back of a length on off, Agarwal pushes it to covers.
Goes wide of the crease and bowls it on middle, Agarwal is once again solid in defense.

Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.

SIX! Another one. Comes to the pitch of the ball and launches it for a maximum over long on.
Tossed up on leg. Blocked  to short leg.

SIX! Tossed up on off, Agarwal gets to the pitch of the ball and launches it back over the bowler's head for a maximum.

FOUR! DEFT! Picked his spot nicely. The bowler is bowling without a point so Agarwal hits this one through that region. It is flatter and outside off, Agarwal waits for it and plays it very late and bags a boundary. Runs coming thick and fast for India now. 14 from the last two.

Change of ends for Keshav Maharaj.

Camps on the back foot to work the ball to the off side.

DRINKS! India's first hour! They have gone through the testing period unscathed. Both Rohit and Agarwal had problems against the new ball which was doing a bit but the important thing is, none of the openers have been dismissed and now, they are looking comfortable out there. South Africa need a couple of wickets quickly. The good thing for them though is they haven't let India score freely. Will fortunes change for them after the break? We'll find out.

Flighted ball on off, Rohit guides it towards cover and gets to the other end.
On a length and around off, this is guided to gully.

FOUR! Exquisite timing once again. Another bowler pays the price for going too full. It is outside off too. Agarwal leans into it and creams it through covers.

Outside off, left alone.

Drags his length back this time and it is kept out.

Outside off, Sharma does not fiddle with it.

Another couple! Fuller in length and on off, Rohit shows the full face of the bat and strokes it towards the bowler. Rabada gets a hand to it, the ball rolls towards long off. Mid on gives it a chase and keeps it down to two.
Goes wide of the crease and angles it into the off pole. Blocked.

Flighted ball on off, Agarwal keeps it out.
Tosses it up on middle, Agarwal plays it to short extra cover.
On off, this is kept out.
On off, Rohit once again manages to keep it out.
A good bumper on middle, Rohit initially looks to pull but then bails out.
OHHH! This is slightly fuller, it comes back in and also skids through. Rohit is a touch late to get his bat down, it hits the inner half and then goes onto hit the pads.
Back of a length again and on off, Rohit plays it to mid off.
On the shorter side and on off, Rohit goes back and keeps it out.

Just outside off again and on a length. Rohit ends up playing outside the line, he gets an inside edge onto the pads.

FOUR! Slashes and gets the result he wanted! Slightly short and outside off, Rohit transfers his weight onto the back foot and slashes at it, it goes past the fielder at gully and into the fence.

EDGY FOUR! Luck now favoring India. This lands on middle and then straightens. Agarwal looks to work it on the leg side but due to the movement, it goes off the leading edge, between gully and second slip and down to the third man fence.
Shortish again on off, blocked.

Rohit maybe expected it to go away again and lets it be. To his luck though, the ball bounces and goes over the middle pole.

Better! This is initially angled into the off pole but then leaves the batter. Agarwal is drawn into playing at it but the ball beats the outside edge by a long way though.
One more wasteful delivery! Short and outside off, it is left alone.
Another one wide outside off, it is left alone. Not a good start by Rabada, he has been too wide.
Goes wide of the crease and angles this one into the off pole. Agarwal goes back and defends it onto the ground.
A tentative poke to end! A good over this by Philander. This starts outside off and then moves away further. Rohit hangs his bat out and the ball once again goes past the outside edge.
Rohit takes a few steps down the track, maybe to negotiate the movement. Philander hence, shortens the length which means the ball has lesser time to do its bit. Rohit blocks it out easily.
This one is outside off, a harmless delivery. Left alone.

BEATEN! Lovely delivery! The South African bowlers are getting the ball to talk here. Not a lot Rohit could have done there. It lands on off and it is on a length. Rohit looks to defend the original trajectory but the ball shapes away after pitching. Whizzes past the outside edge.
Well bowled! This is angled into the batter now, it pitches around off and then nips back in just a touch. Agarwal looks to defend but it goes off the inner half through mid-wicket for one.
One more ball which is wide outside off, it is left alone.
Another leave from Rohit. This one is pitched outside off again.
Another ball which is very wide from the off stump, Rohit lets it go to the keeper. The ball moved further away after pitching.

We are all set to begin! The Indian openers in the form of Rohit Sharma and Mayank Agarwal make their way out to the middle. The South African players are also out in the middle. Here we go...
The players are out for their respective national anthems. First up will be South Africa's followed by the hosts'.

South Africa (Playing XI) - Aiden Markram, Dean Elgar, Theunis de Bruyn, Temba Bavuma, Faf du Plessis(C), Quinton de Kock (WK), Vernon Philander, Senuran Muthusamy (DEBUT), Keshav Maharaj, Dane Piedt, Kagiso Rabada

Faf du Plessis, the Protea skipper, starts by saying that his Toss record is not pretty good in the sub-continent. Adds that few of the players who came here last time have retired and the younger side has a great challenge in front of them. On their playing XI, Faf says that because of the dry surface, they are going with three spinners and two pacers in their team.

The Indian skipper, Kohli says that it's no-brainer. Feels that the wicket is looking good to bat. On the team, Kohli says that Rohit has an excellent opportunity at the top and the team is looking forward to see him. On Saha, Kohli says that he went out because of the injury but remains the best wicket-keeper batter in the world. Talking about the opponents, Kohli says that they are a tough side and it will be hard grind for everyone.
Toss - Kohli flips the coin and he has won the toss. INDIA WILL BAT FIRST.

Pitch report - Murali Kartik is in with the pitch report. He starts by saying that the pitch is always the talk of the town in India. Gavaskar joins him and says that the pitch looks dry and there is hardly any grass. Gavaskar adds that batting will be easy on Day 1. Adds that there are few cracks which will open up as we move ahead. Gavaskar reckons that batting will become difficult from the final session on Day 2. While the spinners will have their say, Sunny G points out that if the pacers use the bouncers well, they can trouble the batters. He says that bat first after winning the toss and post 450 odd runs and the game will be in the grip of the team.

Time for some red-ball action then. The hosts are in red hot form. At home, they are almost invincible. The visitors, they fought well in the T20I series but this is Test cricket. The inexperienced side will look to offer similar resistance to this strong Indian unit. Last time, when they had big names like Hashim Amla and AB de Villiers, Indians had blown them away. Will they be able to present any fight or the hosts will be able to shrug them off like they did last time? We will soon have the answers. Welcome to our coverage of the match. Toss and Pitch Report in a while.

The Indian team will be disappointed after dominating the first two days. Ashwin came out as the star with the ball as he took 7 wickets in all. Jadeja took a couple of wickets and Ishant Sharma took a single wicket. Join us in a short while for the Indian team's response as they will come out to bat for their second innings. Remember, this is a deteriorating surface and it will be tough for the Indian batters as well!

A look back at the South African innings. The Indian spinners started well as they got the visitors reeling at 63/4. However, after that the fightback from the visitors started as they notched up two 100-plus stands and came back into the game. The skipper, Faf du Plessis lead the way by scoring a half century. Quinton de Kock scored a ton but the star of the show was Dean Elgar who was at the crease for the longest time of the three as he scored a daddy hundred. Muthusamy and Kagiso Rabada also contributed some vital runs at the end, reducing the deficit for the visitors.

So, the South African innings has come to a close but much later than a lot of people expected. They have scored 431 and India lead by 71 runs. The hosts will be looking to add at least another 200 runs to this score before giving the South Africans a chance to bat again.

We are all set to begin Day 4! Keshav Maharaj and Senuran Muthusamy make their way out to the middle along with the Indian players.  Mohammed Shami to start the proceedings for the hosts with Maharaj on strike.

Pitch report - Murali Kartik is down with the Indian legend Sunil Gavaskar for the pitch report. Mr. Gavaskar suggests that it looks like more wickets will fall on Day 4 as the cracks have opened up even more. The ball will grip and spin just like on Day 3. Further suggests that the key for the bowlers is to get the batsmen committed on playing strokes and then the bowlers stand a greater chance of taking wickets. Mentions that the ball should be given a lot of air just like Ashwin was doing yesterday. Gavaskar feels that India will be looking to give a target of around 300 to the visitors.

Day 3 belonged to South Africa as they brought the match closer to a draw but with still two innings and six sessions to go, a lot of time is left in the Test match. The standout performers for the Proteas were centurions Dean Elgar and Quinton de Kock but one cannot forget how Faf du Plessis showed how to take the attack to the opposition. Ashwin proved to be one of the few positives for India as he took his 27th 5-fer but there were a few dropped catches from the hosts which would not please their skipper, Virat Kohli.

Welcome to Day 4 of the first Test match between India and South Africa. It has been a riveting contest so far as the momentum has swung like a pendulum. After the first two days when everyone expected South Africa to tumble over, they have proved to be stubborn and the experienced players have given the young guns in their squad a testament of how to overcome all kinds of difficulties. So, will the rainbow nation continue to fight back or will the hosts roll over the lower batting order of the visitors? All these questions will be answered today as we bring you all the action from Visakhapatnam.
... Day 4, Session 1 ...

So, what is in store for us on Day 4? South Africa looked to be on the ropes but they showed a great 'never say die' attitude to harass the Indian players. As for India, they are now in a limbo about what will be their gameplan. Day 4 could prove to be the most crucial day of this Test thus far. Join us on Saturday for all the action from Visakhapatnam on 0930 Local (0400 GMT). Till then, cheers and take care!

Dean Elgar is down for a chat with Sanjay Manjrekar. Thanks Sanjay for his congratulations but then says that the last time he came to India, he was less experienced. But since then, going around the world and playing county cricket has made him much more experienced. On the wickets to be used in India as a suggestion, Elgar smiles and says that definitely not those which were used in 2015! But on a serious note, Dean says that one needs to graft and get used to the pitch and then play his shots. Credits county cricket for enabling him to become a better player. On him hitting the ball in the air and attacking the spinners, Elgar says that these are one of the best batting conditions in Vizag and also that if you attack the spinners, they tend to lose their line. On Quinton de Kock, he calls him a genius with the bat and is certainly not surprised to see him score a century.

As for the Indian bowling, it was a mixed bag. They started well as Ishant Sharma dismissed Bavuma early in the day but after the attack from the South African batters started, they lost their way. They gave away runs freely and could not get a grip on the game. The experienced trio of South Africa was the first real test for them in the game and they were comfortably outplayed by them as they pulled the visitors from a crisis to a more than comfortable position. However, if one bowler is there who does deserve credit is Ravichandran Ashwin who persisted for long spells and got his rewards from time to time as he took a 5-fer and troubled the tail-enders late in the day.

During the first session of the day, everyone expected India to come in and roll over the visitors' batting lineup. However, after the early wicket of Temba Bavuma, the real resistance for them began. Dean Elgar and Faf du Plessis counter-attacked the Indian spin bowling and especially India's ace spin bowler, Ravichandran Ashwin. They stitched a huge partnership of 115  and showed the hosts that they are here to fight and not bow down. Following the departure of the Protean skipper on 55, Quinton de Kock came in and attacked the Indian bowlers as well not letting them settle as he scored 111. The star for the visitors although has to be Dean Elgar who played out an innings of grit as well as style to battle his way through the tough spell on Day 2 and early on Day 3. He made 160 runs and has shown the visitors how to battle against this world class Indian bowling attack.

Flatter and on off, pushed back towards Sir!
Darted full and outside off, de Kock pushes this one towards cover and takes a single. Moves to 97 with that.
DRINKS BREAK. The game is nicely poised now. India looking to hurry into the Protean tail while the South Africans keen to get the deficit into double digits. Or try and bat through the day.
Outside off, a play and a miss.

Appeal for a catch but it is turned down. No bat at all. Full and outside off, Muthusamy gets across to defend but misses. The ball hits his pads and lobs to second slip. A catch appeal ensues but turned down.
Full and well outside off, nicely played out.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Around off, watchfully defended.
Full and outside off, driven towards long off for a single.
Floated on middle and leg, pushed towards mid on by Muthusamy.

Floated outside off, pushed to covers for a single.
On the pads again, de Kock looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
Another one on the pads, de Kock works it towards mid-wicket.
On the pads, worked towards the leg side.

DROPPED AND FOUR! Rahane drops one now and this one should have been caught by his standards! Ashwin pitches this one outside off, gives it a lot of air. It pitches and turns away. Muthusamy looks to defend but it goes off the outside edge towards the left of Rahane at first slip. He dives to his left, gets a hand to it but puts it down. It runs down towards the third man region for a boundary. India could have come back strongly had Rahane held onto that one.
Muthusamy has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Driven towards the mid off region. One run added to the total.
FOUR! Short and outside off, de Kock rocks back and cuts it towards the point region. The ball races to the fence for a boundary.
Floated just outside off, de Kock drives this one towards cover.
De Kock has defended this one as he gets right behind the line of the delivery.
Muthusamy has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery. End of a successful over by Jadeja.
Another one on the pads, works it towards the leg side.
Flatter on the pads, defended by de Kock on the leg side.
Senuran Muthusamy, the debutant, walks out to bat.

OUT! CAUGHT! Finally India get the breakthrough! Brilliant catch by Pujara and the partnership of 164 runs has been broken by Jadeja as he gets his 200th TEST WICKET! This was a floated ball outside off in the rough, Elgar goes for the slog sweep over the mid-wicket fence. He gets just a top edge on it and the ball skies high up in the air. Pujara from mid-wicket runs in hard and dives forward to complete a brilliant catch. Dean Elgar is dismissed after a fantastic knock and India will now look to open up the lower batting order of the visitors. Jadeja is also the second fastest Indian to  reach the 200-wicket landmark. Class!
Huge shout for a catch! Full and outside off, Elgar looks to defend but the ball spins past the outside edge.
Full and around off, watchfully defended.
Around off, watchfully pushed out.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Full and outside off, watchfully blocked.
Landed outside off, de Kock looks to defend but the ball spins away a mile.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Full and around middle and off, driven straight to cover.
Tossed up on off, it has been driven superbly through the covers by Elgar. Two runs added to the total.
EDGED AND FOUR! Luck on South Africa's side it seems. Floated outside off, Elgar looks to defend but does so inside the line. It goes off the outside edge towards the third man region for a boundary.
Floated on middle and off, de Kock pushes this towards mid on and gives the strike to Elgar.
FOUR! Counter-attack by Quinton! Floated outside off in the rough, de Kock reverse sweeps this one towards third man and it races into the fence.

Another chance but de Kock again survives! De Kock looks to defend this one, it takes the inside edge, the ball goes onto the pads and to the left of Saha. He dives to his left but cannot reach to the ball. Fortune favouring the brave?

Tossed up outside off, it turns back in sharply. The ball takes the inside edge of the bat and goes towards mid-wicket for a single. The short leg fielder was interested for a while but it was too wide for him.
Full on middle, de Kock works it towards short mid-wicket, sets off for a single but then sees it is Ravindra Jadeja over there, changes his mind.
Outside off, punched through the covers for a single.
Around off, pushed back to the bowler.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Full and outside off, driven straight to mid off.
Full and around off, watchfully defended.
Ravichandran Ashwin returns. 30-7-101-3 so far.
FOUR! Floated outside off, de Kock drives this one through the cover region gloriously for a boundary.
The batsman flicks it away with a wristy shot

DROPPED BY SAHA! Another dropped catch by Saha and this time it is de Kock who survives. Floated one outside off, de Kock looks to defend this one but the ball sneaks from beneath his bat taking the bottom edge. It goes to Saha who cannot react in time to take the catch and it falls just short of Rahane who tries to dive and take it with his right hand. How dearly will India regret this, only time will tell!
De Kock gets right behind the line of the delivery and blocks it out.
Again tossed up on off, pushed towards mid on this time by de Kock.
Slower through the air outside off, pushed towards mid off by the batter.
On the pads of de Kock, he flicks this one towards square leg and retains strike by taking a single.
Length ball on middle and leg, de Kock pushes this one towards mid on.
FOUR! Beautiful shot! De Kock stands tall on this length ball, gets on top of the bounce and drives this one towards the long off region for a boundary.
Length ball around off, de Kock pushes this one towards cover-point.
Short of a length this time on middle, de Kock pulls this one but straight to the man at mid-wicket.
Length ball just outside off, driven towards mid off by de Kock off the back foot.
Mohammed Shami is back on. 12-3-30-0 so far.
Another one down the leg side, the batsman has flicked the ball off his pads.
Elgar misses his flick and is hit on the pads.
Tossed up on middle and off, Elgar looks to defend but it goes off the inside edge and thuds into the pads.
Full and floated on middle and leg, de Kock pushes this towards mid on for a single.
On the pads this time, Elgar flicks this one towards backward square leg as Vihari dives to his left. The batters take one in the meantime.
Slower through the air outside off, pushed back towards the bowler.
Full and outside off, driven straight to mid off.
The batsman has punched the ball off the back foot.
Landed outside off, left alone.
Outside off, played through point for a run.
Full on middle, flicked through mid-wicket for a single.
A length ball around middle, angling away, de Kock defends it from his crease.
Outside off, left alone by Elgar. A good over for the Proteas!

FOUR! 150 FOR DEAN ELGAR! What an innings this has been by the southpaw! Gritty, determined, tough! Tossed up just outside off, Elgar opens the face of his bat and guides this one towards third man for a boundary.
Tossed up around off, Elgar blocks this one out.
Elgar has driven it straight down the ground.
FOUR! Educated edge this time! Full and floated outside off, Elgar opens the face of his bat but it goes off the outside half of his bat towards the third man fence for another boundary.

Woah! What happened there? FOUR BYES! Full ball pitched outside off, Elgar looks to play the reverse sweep but it spun and kept really low as the ball went beneath Saha towards the fine leg fence for a boundary.
Length ball around off, Elgar cuts it towards point and takes a single.
Now, the change. Cheteshwar Pujara comes in at wide first slip while Rohit goes even wider towards gully.

EDGED AND FOUR! Chance but in the vacant first slip region. Don't know why there is a wide first slip in place but not the mandatory one. A good short of a length ball outside off by Ishant, Elgar tries to keep it down but it goes off the shoulder of the bat towards the vacant first slip region. Saha dives to his left but the ball races to the third man fence. The follow-on has also been avoided with this boundary!
Down the leg side, de Kock tucks it towards mid-wicket and takes a single.
A rare bouncer in this match, down the leg side. Quinton tries to keep it down as he tries to roll his wrists over it but he is hit on the gloves and the ball falls onto the pitch.
Another length ball on middle and off, de Kock blocks it out.
Length ball just outside off, de Kock pushes it towards cover-point.
Full and floated outside off, pushed towards cover by Dean.

First run off the over as de Kock pushes this one towards mid on for a single. This is now the highest score by a South African wicket keeper in India in Tests. De Kock stepping up at the perfect time!
Again on the pads, this time de Kock flicks it towards mid-wicket.
Darted onto the leg pole line, pushed towards the mid on fielder.
Flatter this time outside off, de Kock looks to play at it but bails out eventually.
Full and floated outside off, pushed towards the cover fielder.
Ravindra Jadeja returns. 24-2-82-1 so far.
Runs on the last ball of the over. On the hips of Elgar, he tucks it towards backward square leg where Pujara mops it up. The batters take a couple.
On the pads now, Elgar tucks this towards the leg side.
Another one on the good length, Elgar defends it back towards the bowler.
Attacking the stumps now Ishant, this one keeps a bit low. On middle and off, Elgar brings his bat down in time to block it out.
Jaffa by Ishant now! Length ball just outside off, the ball pitches and nips away. Elgar looks to defend but it goes past his outside edge in a jiffy.
Good start by Ishant but also a loose shot by Elgar! Length ball just outside off, Elgar goes for the drive towards cover but does so inside the line and misses the ball completely.
Finally a pacer to make use of the second new ball. Ishant Sharma it is. 11-2-34-1 so far.
Floated on the boots, Elgar pushes this towards mid on and takes a single to keep strike.
Down the leg side, Elgar blocks this one down.
Fullish and outside off, Elgar pushes this back towards Ashwin.
Again on the pads by Ashwin, this time de Kock flicks this one towards fine leg for a single.
On the pads this time, Elgar flicks this one towards square leg and takes a single.
He blocks this shortish ball out onto the ground towards the off side.

Welcome back to the third session on Day 3. South Africa have crawled their way back into the contest and India have a lot to ponder about right now with Quinton de Kock and Dean Elgar at the crease. Virat Kohli has his troops in a huddle and is giving them a pep talk. Ravichandran Ashwin will start the proceedings for the final session. Dean Elgar facing the first ball.
... Day 3, Session 3 ...

Nothing much happened in this session, but the odd ball has started to keep low. Kohli will be relieved from inside that he will not have to choose to enforce follow-on or not. But he will want his bowlers to get a breakthrough and then run through the lower middle order. Join us back at 3 pm local (0930 GMT).

A dominant session for the Proteas. Not just a good one. They have scored 139 runs in 37 overs, for the loss of just Faf du Plessis. They have come close to avoiding the follow-on on merit, which is by no means, an easy task in India.
Full and around off, watchfully defended. TEA ON DAY 3, SOUTH AFRICA TRAIL BY 210!
Extra bounce! A flighted ball, around middle, de Kock looks to defend but the ball rises sharply and hits him on the glove. He looks shocked, more than surprised.
Full and around middle, pushed towards the bowler.
On middle and leg, tucked through mid-wicket for a single.
Full and around off, watchfully defended.
Around middle and leg, worked through fine leg.

Covers the line of the ball and defends its on the front foot.

Leg bye! On middle and off, the ball spin into Elgar, who gets a thigh pad on it. It slides on to fine leg and they run a single.
Floats it just outside off. Elgar blocks it to silly point.
Ravichandran Ashwin returns. 28-6-98-3 so far.
Full again, once more defended by QdK.
Full and around off, well defended.
On middle and off, worked wide of mid-wicket for one.
Full and outside off, driven straight back to the bowler.
Around middle and leg, worked through fine leg for a run.
Down the leg side, helped through square leg for a single.
Ravindra Jadeja is back on! Just a tape on his hand. 22-2-78-1 so far.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
FOUR! Floated outside off, de Kock comes on the front foot and drives it through coves from the middle of the bat for a boundary.
FOUR! Tossed up outside off, de Kock waits on the back foot and guides the down to third man for a boundary. Deft touch really.
Floated outside off, Elgar angles his bat and guides it to gully for a single.
Goes on the back foot and punches the ball to Kohli at mid off.
Pushed to the cover region by Elgar.
Ravindra Jadeja goes off the field. Seems to be a cut there on his right hand. Umesh Yadav replaces him on the field while Hanuma Vihari replaces him with the ball. 8-1-29-0 so far.
FOUR! Full and outside off, de Kock drives it through the covers for the second boundary of the over!
Full and outside off, QdK looks to defend but the ball goes off the outside edge past slip towards third man. Two runs taken.
Around middle, watchfully defended.

FOUR! Just over and dear me, Jadeja collides into the barriers! But he is fine. Full and outside off, de Kock leans and lofts it over cover. Jadeja runs back but cannot get there. Then, he cannot control his speed and crashes into the boards.
Outside off, dabbed towards backward point.
Full and around off, pushed towards the bowler.

Beaten all ends up! Credit that to the extra bounce from the new ball. Tosses it up on middle and off, it goes on with the angle and beat the outside edge with the bounce. Saha makes a very good take by jumping up.
Takes the ball on the up and plays it straight to the mid off fielder.
Floated on off, de Kock plays it to cover for a single. HALF CENTURY FOR QdK! His 18th in Tests.
Floated on middle and off, Elgar tuns it to the on side for a single.
Tossed up on on off, Elgar plays it back to Jadeja.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Interesting. Spinners from both ends. Ravindra Jadeja is back on. 21-2-76-1 so far.
FOUR! Clean strike! Full and outside off, de Kock leans and drives it through the covers!
Landed outside off, de Kock looks to drive but gets a thick inside edge onto his pads.
Tossed up outside off, driven straight to cover.
Full and outside off, Elgar drives this wide of Ravindra Jadeja at mid off and takes off for a quick single. Had to really hurry in the end.
On middle and off, pushed towards cover again.
Full and around off, pushed towards cover.

The second new ball is due and it has been taken. Kohli and Ashwin are in a discussion. Eventually, the premier off spinner takes it. 26-6-83-3 so far. But we have a delay. Elgar has called for the physio. Seems to be a cramp. The magic spray comes out. On the right elbow.
Covers the line of the ball and blocks it out.
Floated outside off played straight to the cover fielder.
Pushes the ball through the cover region for a single.
FOUR! Floated outside off, driven through the covers for a boundary. Easy pickings really.

Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.

On middle and leg, flicked through mid-wicket for a couple.
Outside off, driven straight to mid off.
250 UP FOR SOUTH AFRICA! How did this come about? Everyone expected them to fold up inside 150. But they have fought. Full on middle, flicked towards mid-wicket for a single.
Full and on middle, pushed towards the bowler.
Similar line, is played  towards mid-wicket.
On middle and leg, driven to mid on.
Good length ball on the pads. de Kock misses his flick. Shami appeals but he himself isn't convinced. The umpire was unmoved since it pitched outside leg.
Full on off, played to the covers for a single.
On the pads played to the leg side.

FOUR! Driven and driven well. Straightish line, Elgar stands tall in his crease and straight drives the ball back past the bowler. Gill on as a sub at mid on chases and makes a valiant effort. It's in vain as the ball wins the race and hits the boundary.
Slow, very slow, plenty of loop, full and around middle, watchfully pushed back.

Nice loop outside off, driven straight to cover.
Full and outside off, driven straight to cover.
Around off, pushed towards the bowler to his left.
Full and outside off, driven straight to cover.
Look who is here! Rohit Sharma smiles. The crowd  cheers. Because he is on to bowl!
On the middle and off line. Elgar, gets behind it and defends solidly.

Around off, driven back to the bowler.
Full and around off, pushed towards cover.
Outside off, pushed towards cover.
Full toss outside off, driven wide of mid off for a single.
On the pads, de Kock gets it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
It has gone overcast. The floodlights have been switched on.
Full outside off, he finally gets a single for his shot through the point region.
Continues with this line on middle and leg, Elgar works it to mid-wicket.
On middle and leg worked to the mid-wicket fielder.
On the pads again this time, de Kock flicks it for a single.
Back of a length ball angling into the pads, de Kock misses the flick and is struck on the knee roll.
Mohammed Shami comes back on, with 8 overs to go for the second new ball. 9-3-21-0 so far.
Around middle and off, Dean uses his wrists to work it with the angle towards short mid-wicket.

Eases this through mid on for a run.

Length ball, outside off, de Kock guides it to gully.

Beaten! De Kock lazily flays at the ball outside off. He is beaten at the half-baked attempt to play the ball.
Ishant slides the ball on to the pads, de Kock flicks it to square leg for a couple.
Back of a length ball outside off, Elgar guides it to third man for one. He's batting really well. This positive intent has been there since yesterday.
A full toss, around middle, pushed through mid on for a run.
Short and outside off, cut through cover for a single.
Full and around off, watchfully defended.
Outside off, de Kock looks to cut but misses. That stayed low!
Quick single pinched. Elgar pushes this slightly wide of Agarwal at point and sets off for a quick single. De Kock responds nicely.
Full and outside off, pushed towards cover.
Back of a length ball, cut to the off side. No run.
Fullish ball outside off, de Kock drives it towards cover. That was a good shot but straight to the fielder.
Good length ball outside off. De Kock defends it on the back foot.
NO BALL! Excess effort from Ishant sees him overstep. The ball goes off the inner half and hits Elgar on the thigh pads. A single taken towards square leg. 50-run stand is up.
Covers the line of the ball and plays it to mid off.
Fuller and outside off, Elgar plays it towards point.
Good length ball, outside off. Elgar drives it to mid off.
Change of pace. Ishant Sharma comes on. 9-2-29-1 so far.
Landed outside off, played straight to point.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
FOUR! Short and outside off, de Kock cuts it through point for a boundary!
Eases this through mid on for one.
Full and outside off, eased through the covers for a run.
Full and outside off, pushed through the covers for a single.
Hanuma Vihari into the attack again. 3-1-9-0 so far.
Covers the line of the shortish ball and blocks it.
That ball has taken the inside edge of the batsman and thudded into his pads.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
FOUR! 19 runs off the last 5 balls! Full and outside off, de Kock looks to defend but the ball goes off his outside edge and and races to the third man fence. Why wasn't there any slip in place?

SIX! That is big! Seemed like a top edge but it has cleared the ropes. Full and outside off, de Kock gets down on a knee and aims for the slog sweep. Hanuma Vihari at mid-wicket looks interested for a bit but then just sees the ball sailing over.
Jadeja tosses it up outside off, Elgar pokes it to covers. RJ chases it himself. Still concedes a single.
FOUR! Classy hit. Full and outside off, de Kock leans and drives this through the covers. The ball races away.

FOUR! Not cleanly hit but will still get runs. And four of them. Full and outside off, de Kock looks to go over the top but mistimes it. However, Mayank Agarwal is inside the circle at mid on and the ball clears him. One bounce and into the ropes.
Quicker, around middle, pushed towards short mid-wicket.
Nicely flighted outside off, plenty of loop, de Kock gets down and drives but finds cover.
Full and around middle, flicked straight to short mid-wicket.
Tossed up outside off, driven straight to cover.
Elgar plays that off the front foot and into the ground.

On the pads  and it's worked away to the on side.

Looks to sweep but misses. It hits his pads.

Around middle, tucked straight to mid-wicket for a single.

On off, worked to the on side.

Flighted on a length, it spins in sharply, de Kock plays it with the spin to square leg for one.
Tossed up on off, de Kock comes on the front foot to defend.

DRINKS BREAK. This is an extended session, hence we will be having two breaks. A good start for India after Lunch. They kept it tight and eventually, forced an error from du Plessis to get his wicket. South Africa are miles away from avoiding the follow-on but given that 60-plus overs have already been bowled, looks highly improbable that Kohli will enforce it.
Flighted outside off, Elgar misses the ball due to the spin on it. It hits his pads.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
Comes on the front foot and blocks the ball.
The ball has taken the inside edge of the batsman and thudded into his pad.

Darted in on off, it comes in with the angle and Elgar defends.
Full and around off, well blocked out.
Down the leg side, de Kock misses his flick and is hit on the pads.
Around off, pushed towards the off side.
Full and outside off, watchfully blocked out.

SAFE. But what a throw from Ashwin. Full and outside off, Elgar leans and drives it towards cover. Ashwin picks the ball up and has a shy at the bowler's end. Jadeja takes his hand off at the last moment and the ball hits the stumps and the bails fall later. It is referred upstairs and replays show that Elgar is well in.
An appeal! For what? A run out. Apparently, the bails have fallen down on a direct hit. Kohli is pumped up. Here come the replays. Elgar is in.
On middle, flicked towards short mid-wicket where Virat Kohli makes a tumbling stop to his left.
On the pads comes in with the angle, de Kock misses his flick. It hits him on the pads.

Dropped by Rohit! Tough chance though. Tossed up outside off, and spinning away, de Kock closes the face of his bat too soon. Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
Played to the point region by the batsman.
Goes on the back foot and uppishly cuts the ball through point.

Another quicker one outside off, pushed towards cover.
Fired in on middle and leg, pushed towards the leg side.

Goes on the back foot and pokes it back to Jadeja.
Floated on middle, played back to the bowler.
Tossed up on middle and off, driven to covers for a couple.
Ravindra Jadeja is back on. 16-1-56-1 so far.
Full and outside off, Elgar leans and drives it through the covers. Mayank Agarwal chases it from the circle and slides near the fence to stop the boundary. Two runs taken.
Around off, defended from the crease.
Off the mark straightaway. Works this through mid-wicket for a single.
Quinton de Kock walks in at number 7, replacing his captain. Two left-handers at the crease now.

'YES!' screams Virat Kohli on the stump mic as he rushes to celebrate with his number 3. The 115-run stand is broken and South Africa are 125 away from legally making India bat again. Though doubt that Kohli will enforce the follow-on now.
Nice flight outside off, worked straight to widish mid on.
Flighted outside off, spinning in, tucked towards short mid-wicket.

On the pads, it's flicked off the pads, to short mid-wicket.
Full ball around off driven to mid off.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
No ball! Shami oversteps. Fullish ball on middle and off, Elgar firmly blocked it.

Full and down the leg side, Faf misses his flick and is hit on the pads.
Around off, Faf pushes this a bit too hard and the ball goes off the upper half towards mid on. Almost carries!

FOUR! Fine shot. A bit of a top spinner, outside off, Faf gets down and mows a slog sweep, through mid-wicket. There is Ravindra Jadeja at deep mid-wicket, 15-20 yards inside the circle but the ball is finer, to his right.
Faster one, outside off, blocked towards short mid-wicket.
Nicely tossed up outside off, well defended.

We are back for the second session! Dean Elgar and Faf du Plessis make their way out to the middle. Shami to begin the proceedings for the hosts with Dean Elgar on strike.
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

The hosts, on the other hand, were not up to the mark today especially the spinners as they were put off their lengths by some attacking play from the South African batsmen out in the middle. Ishant Sharma bowled well and was rewarded with the wicket of Bavuma. India are still ahead in the game but would look to get quick wickets after the Lunch break. Join us in a while for all the action.

The visitors although lost the wicket of Bavuma early, du Plessis and Elgar have stitched a magnificent stand which has got them to a score of above 150. Elgar is on course to his 12th Test ton while du Plessis is close to his half-ton. They still have a lot of work to do and need to continue the good work after the break.
First session which has belonged to the Proteas in this Test match. They have played counter-attacking cricket and have added 114 runs in 30 overs with the loss of just one wicket.
Last ball of this session, and du Plessis negotiates it nicely as he dabs this one onto the pitch. He starts walking off the field and that will be LUNCH ON DAY 3!
On the pads, du Plessis flicks it away with a wristy shot towards the leg side.
Beaten! Jadeja pitches this one outside off, it spins away from Faf. He looks to defend at it but misses the line of the delivery as it beats the outside edge of his blade.

We are all set to begin! Dean Elgar and Temba Bavuma make their way out to the middle along with the Indian players. Bavuma will be on strike facing Ishant Sharma. The temperature is very high here in Visakhapatnam and we can expect a hot and tiring day for both the sides. Day 3 is underway...

Pitch Report - Murali Kartik is there for the pitch report along with Sunil Gavaskar. Sunny G says that the ball was keeping low yesterday and it will continue to happen today. He further says the odd ball will bounce extra as the cracks have opened up and it will grip and spin. The Proteas need to show a lot of grit and determination to play on this track just like Mayank Agarwal did yesterday.

Hello and a warm welcome to the coverage of Day 3 of the first Test match between India and South Africa. The hosts are running away with the game after posting a score of above 500 and then picking up three wickets late on Day 2. The visitors, on the other hand, were poor with both bat and ball. They had no answer to the bowling of Jadeja and Ashwin. They would be hoping to bat for as long as possible in order to have any chance to get closer to India's score. Will the tourists show some fight or will India continue to dominate? Join us in a while to find out.
... Day 3, Session 1 ...

Going into Day 3, the hosts hold the upper hand and would look to bowl out South Africa as soon as possible. The visitors have their backs to the wall and will have to bat out of their skins to compete. Day 3 is said to be the moving day and this promises to be no different. That's all from us. Join us at 0930 local (0400 GMT) for an exciting day. Until then, cheers!

Murali Kartik is down with Mayank Agarwal for an interview. He is extremely happy with his knock and says that he cannot describe his feelings in words. Feels that if he and Rohit keep batting like this, it will be great for the team. Tells that the key to success in a partnership is to stay patient as at times when you are in good touch, you get carried away with your shot selection. He is all praise for Rohit Sharma for the way he handles the spinners. Tells that early on Day 1, there was something in the pitch for the bowlers but later on it settled down into a good batting surface. Informs that post the Lunch break on Day 2, the pitch started to assist the spinners and we also witnessed some uneven bounce. Feels that had Ashwin and Jadeja bowled on Day 1, they would have kept pressure and bowled great lines. Concludes by saying that the spinners will get a lot of purchase with the way the pitch has started to behave.

South Africa had a tricky period before Stumps to survive but they failed to deal with the might of the Indian spinners. Both Ashwin and Jadeja were too hot to handle and the Saffas lost three wickets in a jiffy. Had Bavuma not got dropped, it would have been even worse for the visiting side. Dean Elgar survived but he never looked comfortable. Big task ahead on Day 3.

The visitors were abysmal with the ball and struggled for wickets throughout. Apart from a period in the afternoon session where South Africa snapped up four wickets, there wasn't much happening for them. Their frontline spinners flopped miserably and the speedster Kagiso Rabada was also flavourless. The decision to pick three spinners did not work for South Africa.

Earlier in the day, India started from where they left off on Day 1 with Rohit Sharma and Mayank Agarwal continuing to milk runs. Rohit Sharma was the first wicket to fall as he was dismissed for an impressive 176. Mayank Agarwal, as mentioned earlier, carried on to get his maiden double ton which boosted the total of India. The other batsmen also chipped in with valuable runs before India decided to declare on 502/7!

After the outstanding work done by the Indian batsmen, their spinners got into the act to pick up three quick wickets which sweetened things further for the home team. The spinners, Ashwin and Jadeja, were on target from the word go and picked up three wickets between them.

Another day which has been dominated by India! They have this Test match firmly in their grasp and that's mainly due to the contributions of their new opening pair. One half of that pair, Mayank Agarwal, scored a double ton today and is leading his team off the ground.
